{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648501"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:54:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:54:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18316"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18316"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.09,0.85,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78653"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11034"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18316"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63996"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10851"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25607"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78653"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements is true regarding musculoskeletal tuberculosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It is primarily diagnosed through blood tests","It is not contagious","It can affect any bone, joint, or bursa","It is caused by a virus","It only affects the spine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMusculoskeletal tuberculosis represents an extrapulmonary manifestation of tuberculosis infection that can involve skeletal structures throughout the body. The causative organism is \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E, which can cause destructive changes in bones and joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELet\u0027s examine why each option is correct or incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is primarily diagnosed through blood tests\u003C/strong\u003E - Diagnosis typically requires a combination of imaging studies and microbiological confirmation, not just blood tests\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is not contagious\u003C/strong\u003E - While the bone and joint manifestations themselves aren\u0027t directly transmissible, the underlying tuberculosis infection can spread between people via respiratory droplets\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt can affect any bone, joint, or bursa\u003C/strong\u003E - This is correct. While the spine (Pott\u0027s disease) is most commonly affected, any skeletal structure can be involved\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is caused by a virus\u003C/strong\u003E - Incorrect as tuberculosis is caused by the bacterium \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E, not a virus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt only affects the spine\u003C/strong\u003E - While spinal involvement is common, tuberculosis can affect any part of the musculoskeletal system\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Musculoskeletal tuberculosis can affect any bone, joint, or bursa in the body.","The spine is the most common site for musculoskeletal tuberculosis, known as Pott\u0027s disease.","Musculoskeletal tuberculosis is caused by the bacterium Mycobacterium tuberculosis.","Symptoms of musculoskeletal tuberculosis can include pain, swelling, and reduced range of motion.","Diagnosis of musculoskeletal tuberculosis often involves imaging and microbiological testing."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Mohan, H. (2018). Textbook of pathology. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers","Momodu II, Savaliya V. Osteomyelitis. [Updated 2023 May 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532250/","Folpe, A., \u0026 Nielsen, G. P. (Eds.). (2022). Bone and Soft Tissue Pathology E-Book: A Volume in the Foundations in Diagnostic Pathology Series. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63996"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18316"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63996"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T21:13:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T00:17:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11034"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78653"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"se